jpg" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide4-b-2.jpg?resize=400%2C400 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide4-b-2.jpg?resize=800%2C800 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide4-b-2.jpg?resize=1200%2C1200 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide4-b-2.jpg?resize=1600%2C1600 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide4-b-2.jpg?resize=2000%2C2000 2000w"></div><div class="intro-slide--image intro-image--06"><img id="intro-5-gas-1" src="https://propublica.s3.amazonaws.com/projects/graphics/2026-oil-climate-universities/02_assets/intro_sketches/2026-climate-u-intro--slide5-a.jpg"> <img id="intro-5-gas-1" class="" alt="" width="2000" height="2000" loading="lazy" js-autosizes src="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-a.jpg" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-a.jpg?resize=400%2C400 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-a.jpg?resize=800%2C800 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-a.jpg?resize=1200%2C1200 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-a.jpg?resize=1600%2C1600 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-a.jpg?resize=2000%2C2000 2000w"> <img id="intro-5-gas-2" class="" alt="" width="2000" height="2000" loading="lazy" js-autosizes src="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-b.jpg" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-b.jpg?resize=400%2C400 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-b.jpg?resize=800%2C800 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-b.jpg?resize=1200%2C1200 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-b.jpg?resize=1600%2C1600 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/2026-climate-u-intro-slide5-b.jpg?resize=2000%2C2000 2000w"></div></div><div class="intro-slide--texts"><div class="intro-slide--text intro-slide--text-01"><p>In the 1990s, even as they denied the reality of climate change, oil company executives were quietly funding research that favored climate fixes that would protect their businesses.</p></div><div class="intro-slide--text intro-slide--text-02"><p>They poured billions of dollars into the nation’s top universities, building what we now think of as the most prestigious and advanced climate research centers in the world.</p></div><div class="intro-slide--text intro-slide--text-03"><p>With their work bolstered by fossil fuel money and burnished by the reputations of their schools, scientists published papers that legitimized the climate change solutions the industry preferred.</p></div><div class="intro-slide--text intro-slide--text-04"><p>Those solutions steered the conversation away from breaking our dependence on oil and gas, and instead justified an approach of <em>pollute now, clean up later</em>.</p></div><div class="intro-slide--text intro-slide--text-05"><p>Many of those solutions just don’t work at the scale that is needed. But magical thinking about silver-bullet technologies has now been baked into the models that inform global policy.</p></div><div class="intro-slide--text intro-slide--text-06"><p>It may be too late to undo the damage.</p></div></div></div><header class="p-custom-opener--centered" style="margin-top: var(--vert-rhythm-lg);
        margin-bottom: var(--vert-rhythm-lg);" data-pp-location="article opener"><div class="p-custom-opener-text-wrapper"><div class="p-custom-opener-hed-container"><h1 class="p-custom-opener__hedblock hed-1">Carbon</h1><h1 class="p-custom-opener__hedblock hed-2">Captured</h1><div class="hed-mask"><div class="hed-wave"></div></div></div><h2 class="p-custom-opener__dek">How the fossil fuel industry turned the plan to solve climate change into a plan to save itself</h2><h2 class="p-custom-opener__series-bug">An investigative series by ProPublica and Drilled</h2><div class="p-article-meta-1 p-article-meta-1--center"><div class="p-article-meta-1__section-actions p-article-meta-1__section-actions--center" data-pp-location="story-tools"><script type="application/json" class="svelte-config">{"componentName":"ShareTools","props":{"pageUrl":"https://projects.propublica.org/carbon-captured/","pageTitle":"Carbon Captured — ProPublica"}}</script><div style="display: contents"><!--[--><div class="share-tools" data-pp-click="" data-pp-location="share tools"><!--[--><!--[--><!--$s1--><!--[0--><div class="svelte-1ear6bd button--circle" style="display: contents; --button-bg-color: var(--p-dyn-color-white); --button-text-color: var(--p-dyn-color-black); --button-border: 1px solid var(--p-dyn-color-gray-01); --button-font-size: var(--p-scale-4);"><!--[--><!----><button data-button-root="true" type="button" tabindex="0" id="bits-s1" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" data-popover-trigger="" aria-label="Share"><span aria-hidden="true" style="display: contents"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><g clip-path="url(#clip0_149_321)"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M4 11C4.55228 11 5 11.4477 5 12V20C5 20.2652 5.10536 20.5196 5.29289 20.7071C5.48043 20.8946 5.73478 21 6 21H18C18.2652 21 18.5196 20.8946 18.7071 20.7071C18.8946 20.5196 19 20.2652 19 20V12C19 11.4477 19.4477 11 20 11C20.5523 11 21 11.4477 21 12V20C21 20.7957 20.6839 21.5587 20.1213 22.1213C19.5587 22.6839 18.7957 23 18 23H6C5.20435 23 4.44129 22.6839 3.87868 22.1213C3.31607 21.5587 3 20.7956 3 20V12C3 11.4477 3.44772 11 4 11Z" fill="currentColor"></path><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M11.2929 1.29289C11.6834 0.902369 12.3166 0.902369 12.7071 1.29289L16.7071 5.29289C17.0976 5.68342 17.0976 6.31658 16.7071 6.70711C16.3166 7.09763 15.6834 7.09763 15.2929 6.70711L12 3.41421L8.70711 6.70711C8.31658 7.09763 7.68342 7.09763 7.29289 6.70711C6.90237 6.31658 6.90237 5.68342 7.29289 5.29289L11.2929 1.29289Z" fill="currentColor"></path><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 1C12.5523 1 13 1.44772 13 2V15C13 15.5523 12.5523 16 12 16C11.4477 16 11 15.5523 11 15V2C11 1.44772 11.4477 1 12 1Z" fill="currentColor"></path></g><defs><clipPath id="clip0_149_321"><rect width="24" height="24" fill="white"></rect></clipPath></defs></svg><!----></span><!----><!----></button><!----><!--]--></div><!----><!--]--><!----><!--]--> <!--[--><!--[-1--><!--]--><!--]--><!----><!----><!--]--></div><!--]--></div></div></div></div></header></div><article class="p-grid-text-container newsapp-story"><div class="secondary-text"><p>An investigation by ProPublica and Drilled has found that fossil fuel companies have been funding climate research at prestigious U.S. universities for more than 30 years. Their support has helped amplify the work of scientists who promote the idea that we can stop the climate crisis without breaking our dependence on oil, gas and coal.</p><p>The research produced by those schools in turn shaped global climate models, as well as the policy and technology solutions adopted by governments around the world.</p><p>Ultimately, it fostered a misperception that climate change could be solved without dramatically curtailing fossil fuels — a notion that has delayed emissions cuts by decades.</p><p>Corporate funders sponsored entire centers, paid the salaries of researchers, kept offices on campus and in some cases had veto power over projects.</p><p>Companies maintain they are supporting innovation and needed science. Universities say that with safeguards, sponsorship enhances research programs while preserving academic independence.</p><p>Still, the impact of funding constitutes a pattern that Benjamin Franta, an associate professor of climate litigation at University of Oxford, called the “colonization of academia.”</p></div><div class="series-list-container"><h3 class="series-list-title">In this Series</h3><div class="series-list-item"><div class="series-list-img"><a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/wedges-climate-research-bp-fossil-fuel-princeton"><picture><source media="(min-width: 78em)" width="2393" height="2393" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-1x1-1.jpg?resize=400%2C400 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-1x1-1.jpg?resize=800%2C800 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-1x1-1.jpg?resize=1200%2C1200 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-1x1-1.jpg?resize=1600%2C1600 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-1x1-1.jpg?resize=2000%2C2000 2000w"><img alt="" width="2889" height="1926" loading="lazy" js-autosizes src="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-PromoA.jpg" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-PromoA.jpg?resize=400%2C267 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-PromoA.jpg?resize=800%2C533 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-PromoA.jpg?resize=1200%2C800 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-PromoA.jpg?resize=1600%2C1067 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Wedges-PromoA.jpg?resize=2000%2C1333 2000w"></picture></a></div><div class="series-list-item-text"><h4 class="series-list-item-hed"><a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/wedges-climate-research-bp-fossil-fuel-princeton">How Oil Execs Shaped A Landmark Climate Study</a></h4><h5 class="series-list-item-dek">BP created an elite Princeton research center to address the climate problem without getting off fossil fuels. Its key work, a paper known as “Wedges,” shaped climate discourse for a generation.</h5><p class="series-list-link"><a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/wedges-climate-research-bp-fossil-fuel-princeton">Read Story</a></p></div></div><div class="series-list-item"><div class="series-list-img"><a href="https://projects.propublica.org/why-carbon-capture-cant-solve-climate-change"><picture><source media="(min-width: 78em)" width="1748" height="2040" loading="lazy" js-autosizes src="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Intro-Crop.jpg" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Intro-Crop.jpg?resize=400%2C467 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Intro-Crop.jpg?resize=800%2C934 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Intro-Crop.jpg?resize=1200%2C1400 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Intro-Crop.jpg?resize=1600%2C1867 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Intro-Crop.jpg?resize=2000%2C2334 2000w"><img alt="" width="2400" height="1600" loading="lazy" js-autosizes src="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Featured-1-2.jpg" srcset="https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Featured-1-2.jpg?resize=400%2C267 400w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Featured-1-2.jpg?resize=800%2C533 800w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Featured-1-2.jpg?resize=1200%2C800 1200w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Featured-1-2.jpg?resize=1600%2C1067 1600w, https://www.propublica.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CCS-Featured-1-2.jpg?resize=2000%2C1333 2000w"></picture></a></div><div class="series-list-item-text"><h4 class="series-list-item-hed"><a href="https://projects.propublica.org/why-carbon-capture-cant-solve-climate-change">Why Carbon Capture Can’t Conceivably Solve Climate Change</a></h4><h5 class="series-list-item-dek">For decades, oil companies have funded universities’ research into climate change “solutions” that would not require the public to stop using oil and gas. Carbon capture is one of their favored ideas. One snag: It won’t fix the climate crisis.</h5><p class="series-list-link"><a href="https://projects.propublica.org/why-carbon-capture-cant-solve-climate-change">Read Story</a></p></div></div></div><h3 class="series-list-closer">More stories to come in 2026.</h3><p class="series-contrib">Illustrations by R. Kikuo Johnson. Visual editing by <a href="https://www.propublica.org/people/alex-bandoni">Alex Bandoni</a>. Design and development by <a href="https://www.propublica.org/people/anna-donlan">Anna Donlan</a>.</p></article></main><script type="application/json" class="svelte-config">{"componentName":"SiteFooter","props":{}}</script><div style="display: contents"><!--[--><footer class="svelte-efuts5"><div class="p-grid-container"><!--[0--><div class="site-footer__newsletter-signup-wrapper svelte-efuts5"><h2 class="svelte-efuts5">Go behind the scenes of ProPublica’s biggest investigations.</h2><form class="newsletter-signup svelte-1rwztwi" action="https://signup.propublica.org/newsletter/turing" method="post" name="newsletterSignup"><label for="newsletter-signup-email-1" class="p-a11y">Email Address:</label> <input class="newsletter-signup__input svelte-1rwztwi" type="email" placeholder="Your email address" id="newsletter-signup-email-1" name="email" required=""><div class="svelte-1ear6bd" style="display: contents; --button-bg-color: var(--p-dyn-color-black); --button-text-color: var(--p-dyn-color-white); --button-border: none; --button-font-size: var(--p-scale-4);"><!--[--><!----><button data-button-root="true" type="submit" tabindex="0" 